# Physics update

## 1. Node repulsion

Every node repels every other node.

```javascript
function updatePhysics() {
  // pairwise repulsion
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

      const force = config.repulsion / (dist * dist);
      const fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      const fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }
```

This is basically inverse-square repulsion.

---

## 2. Spring links

Each link acts like a spring with a `rest` length and spring constant `k`.

```javascript
  // spring constraints
  for (let i = 0; i < links.length; i++) {
    const na = getNode(links[i].a);
    const nb = getNode(links[i].b);
    if (!na || !nb) continue;

    const dx = nb.x - na.x;
    const dy = nb.y - na.y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

    const stretch = dist - links[i].rest;
    const force = (links[i].k || config.springK) * stretch;

    na.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    na.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nb.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nb.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }
```

So:
- if two linked nodes are too far apart, they’re pulled together
- if too close, they’re pushed apart

---

## 3. Damping + center gravity + integration

Each node:
- gets velocity damped
- is nudged toward center `(400, 300)`
- position is advanced by velocity

```javascript
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    nodes[i].vx *= config.damping;
    nodes[i].vy *= config.damping;

    nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * config.gravity;
    nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * config.gravity;

    nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
    nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
  }
}
```

This keeps the graph from drifting away forever.

